  "local_port": 45328,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Do I really need to buy tires in pairs?",
  "response": "Whether you need to buy tires in pairs depends on several factors, including the type of vehicle you drive, the specific tire requirements, and the condition of your existing tires. Here are some general guidelines:\n\n1. **Front-Wheel Drive Vehicles**: It's generally recommended to replace tires in pairs on the front axle because these vehicles rely on the front tires for both steering and traction.\n\n2. **Rear-Wheel Drive Vehicles**: For these vehicles, it's typically advised to replace tires in pairs on the rear axle since the rear tires provide the primary traction.\n\n3. **All-Wheel Drive and Four-Wheel Drive Vehicles**: For optimal performance and safety, it's best to replace all four tires at the same time. If that's not possible, replace them in pairs on the same axle, ensuring that the new tires go on the rear axle.\n\n4. **Tread Depth and Condition**: If the tread depth on your existing tires varies significantly, it's a good idea to replace them in pairs to maintain even traction and handling.\n\n5. **Safety and Performance**: Replacing tires in pairs helps maintain balanced handling and braking performance. Mixing new and old tires can lead to uneven wear and compromised safety.\n\n**In Summary**: While it's not always strictly necessary to buy tires in pairs, doing so is generally recommended for safety and performance reasons. If budget constraints are an issue, consult with a tire professional to determine the best course of action for your specific situation.",
